"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/752989","Ministry of Justice","false","2017-07-25","<p>A consultation stage impact assessment was published in November 2016 and is available at <a href="https://consult.justice.gov.uk/digital-communications/reforming-soft-tissue-injury-claims/" target="_blank">https://consult.justice.gov.uk/digital-communications/reforming-soft-tissue-injury-claims/</a>.</p><p>A validated impact assessment detailing the estimated savings to motor insurance premiums arising from the Government’s whiplash reforms, including the data sources and evidence used, will be published alongside the legislation which was announced in the Queen’s Speech.</p><p>The Government will continue to monitor the industry’s reaction to these reforms closely and will consider further action to make sure the savings are passed on if required.</p>","Aylesbury","Mr David Lidington","5589","2017-07-25T14:11:49.163Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/752989/answer","Biography information for Sir David Lidington","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/752989/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/752989/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2017-07-17","Personal Injury: Compensation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what assessment his Department has made of the level of potential savings to motorists as a result of proposed reforms to claims for whiplash; and if he will place in the Library that analysis.","false","Biography information for Richard Burgon","Leeds East","Richard Burgon","5584"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/752990","Ministry of Justice","false","2017-07-25","<p>The named prisons became reform prisons in July 2016 and acted as trailblazers for greater autonomy. They were given considerable freedom to innovate, supported by greater authority over their finances, policies and processes.</p><p> </p><p>Building on the successful work of reform prisons, we have empowered governors across the estate by giving them the levers and controls they need to drive forward reform within their prisons.</p><p> </p><p>These freedoms were announced in the Prison Safety and Reform White Paper. The reform prisons will continue to benefit from these.</p>","Aylesbury","Mr David Lidington",,"2017-07-25T13:50:20.01Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/752990/answer","Biography information for Sir David Lidington","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/752990/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/752990/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2017-07-17","Prisons","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what the current status is of HMP Holme House, HMP Ranby, HMP Kirklevington Grange, HMP Coldingly and HMP Highdown; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Richard Burgon","Leeds East","Richard Burgon","5591"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/752991","Ministry of Justice","false","2017-07-20","<p>A process evaluation is underway on the pilot prisons and this learning has informed the development of the additional powers for governors announced in the white paper. Work is underway to develop an evaluation strategy for the full Prison Reform programme, which will incorporate the additional powers for governors.</p>","East Surrey","Mr Sam Gyimah",,"2017-07-20T16:58:56.88Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/752991/answer","Biography information for Mr Sam Gyimah","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/752991/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/752991/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2017-07-17","Prisons: Pilot Schemes","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what assessment he has made of the effectiveness of pilot prisons and additional powers for governors; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Richard Burgon","Leeds East","Richard Burgon","5432"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/752992","Ministry of Justice","false","2017-07-20","<p>On 3 November 2016, the then Secretary of State for Justice published a White Paper on Prison Safety and Reform outlining the Ministry of Justice’s plans for radical reform of the prison system.</p><p> </p><p>This included an ambitious agenda to modernise the prison estate, improve education and empower governors, to help tackle violence, reduce reoffending and keep staff and prisoners safe.</p><p> </p><p>As part of our wholescale reforms, we are investing £1.3bn to modernise the estate. This will include closing older prisons that are not fit for purpose, and creating in their place high-quality, modern establishments</p><p> </p><p>On 22 March 2017, we announced plans, subject to planning approvals, value for money and affordability, to build four modern prisons: adjacent to HM Prison Full Sutton in Yorkshire (with a pre-planning consultation event held on 11 and 12 April 2017), Port Talbot in Neath, and redevelop HM Prison and Young Offender Institution Rochester in Kent and HM Prison and Young Offender Institution Hindley, in Greater Manchester. This is in addition to the plans previously announced for new sites at former HMP Wellingborough and HM Prison and Young Offender Institution Glen Parva.</p><p> </p><p>On the 19 July 2017 we announced that we still plan to redevelop the prisons at Rochester and Hindley as part of our prison modernisation programme. However, cells at these sites will be kept in use for now, as part of forward-planning for the estate.</p><p> </p><p>No further decisions have been made beyond those that have already been announced.</p>","East Surrey","Mr Sam Gyimah",,"2017-07-20T14:40:49.067Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/752992/answer","Biography information for Mr Sam Gyimah","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/752992/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/752992/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2017-07-17","Prison Accommodation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, when he plans to publish proposals on the future of the prison estate in England and Wales.","false","Biography information for Richard Burgon","Leeds East","Richard Burgon","5433"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/752993","Ministry of Justice","false","2017-07-20","<p>Our reforms will make it easier for vulnerable users to access justice including victims and witnesses. Our modernisation and digitisation of the courts system will streamline and simplify many complex court processes.</p><p>We are building digital services which are accessible to all. In doing so, HMCTS is researching and testing with a wide range of user groups – including the elderly, the young, vulnerable groups, geographically remote users and users with low literacy and/or low IT literacy. We are using the insights and research findings from these groups to help us redesign our services to be easier to understand and navigate for all.</p><p>We recognise that some people will need support to use digital services, and HMCTS is designing a range of assisted digital support channels to be available for this purpose. Our assisted digital support services will cover a range of channels, from web chat or telephone assistance through to more intensive face to face support. Access to paper channels will be maintained in some services for those who need them. Plans for future assisted digital support services formed part of the consultation ‘<a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/consultations/transforming-our-courts-and-tribunals" target="_blank">Transforming our Justice System’</a>, published in September 2016.</p>","Esher and Walton","Dominic Raab",,"2017-07-20T16:01:43.47Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/752993/answer","Biography information for Dominic Raab","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/752993/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/752993/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2017-07-17","Courts: Digital Technology","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what assessment his Department has made of the impact of digitalisation of court services on the ability of vulnerable people to access those services; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Richard Burgon","Leeds East","Richard Burgon","5434"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/752994","Ministry of Justice","false","2017-07-25","<p>The information requested could only be obtained at disproportionate cost.</p>","Aylesbury","Mr David Lidington",,"2017-07-25T13:50:43.75Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/752994/answer","Biography information for Sir David Lidington","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/752994/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/752994/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2017-07-17","Prisons: Security","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, how many cell searches have been conducted in the period between one prisoner moving out of a cell and another moving in, in each of the last three years.","false","Biography information for Richard Burgon","Leeds East","Richard Burgon","5592"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/752995","Ministry of Justice","false","2017-07-25","<p>A consultation stage impact assessment was published in November 2016 and is available at <a href="https://consult.justice.gov.uk/digital-communications/reforming-soft-tissue-injury-claims/" target="_blank">https://consult.justice.gov.uk/digital-communications/reforming-soft-tissue-injury-claims/</a>.</p><p>A validated impact assessment detailing the estimated savings to motor insurance premiums arising from the Government’s whiplash reforms, including the data sources and evidence used, will be published alongside the legislation which was announced in the Queen’s Speech.</p><p>The Government will continue to monitor the industry’s reaction to these reforms closely and will consider further action to make sure the savings are passed on if required.</p>","Aylesbury","Mr David Lidington","5584","2017-07-25T14:11:49.223Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/752995/answer","Biography information for Sir David Lidington","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/752995/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/752995/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2017-07-17","Personal Injury: Compensation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, whether he plans to bring forward legislative proposals to ensure that insurance companies return savings which accrue to them from proposed whiplash reforms to their customers rather than their shareholders.","false","Biography information for Richard Burgon","Leeds East","Richard Burgon","5589"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/752996","Ministry of Justice","false","2017-07-25","<p>The illicit supply of drugs undermines the safety and security of prisons. We are taking urgent and decisive action tackle those behind this criminal enterprise.</p><p> </p><p>In the 12 months to June 2017, the prison with the largest weight of drugs found was HMP Altcourse with a drug weight of 17.1kg seized.</p>","Aylesbury","Mr David Lidington",,"2017-07-25T13:51:43.053Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/752996/answer","Biography information for Sir David Lidington","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/752996/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/752996/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2017-07-17","Prisons: Drugs","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, in which prison the largest amount of drugs was seized in the last 12 months.","false","Biography information for Richard Burgon","Leeds East","Richard Burgon","5590"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/752997","Ministry of Justice","false","2017-07-25","<p>We have carried out a comprehensive review of the probation system to improve outcomes for offenders and communities while making sure public protection remains our top priority. As part of this work we have engaged with probation providers and staff, both in Community Rehabilitation Companies and the National Probation Service. On 19 July 2017 I laid a written statement which provided an update on our work to improve the delivery of probation services.</p>","Aylesbury","Mr David Lidington",,"2017-07-25T13:53:30.137Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/752997/answer","Biography information for Sir David Lidington","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/752997/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/752997/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2017-07-17","Probation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, when his Department plans to carry out a review of the Transforming Rehabilitation programme; and if he will consult staff representatives during that review.","false","Biography information for Richard Burgon","Leeds East","Richard Burgon","5585"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/752998","Ministry of Justice","false","2017-07-25","<p>The Electronic Monitoring Programme has an Authority Programme Board, chaired by the Senior Responsible Owner and reports regularly to HM Prison and Probation Service Agency’s Executive Committee and to the Department’s Investment Committee.</p><p> </p><p>The Senior Responsible Owner of the electronic monitoring programme has successfully completed the Major Projects Leadership Programme and the Programme Director who reports to him has completed the Project Leadership Programme.</p><p> </p><p>The Department’s Portfolio team attend the Authority Programme Board and provide oversight of the Departmental Change Portfolio to ensure it is aligned to strategy, is achievable and affordable; assesses the effectiveness of project governance and controls, and; provides assurance that the portfolio remains on track for effective delivery.</p>","Aylesbury","Mr David Lidington",,"2017-07-25T13:52:41.937Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/752998/answer","Biography information for Sir David Lidington","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/752998/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/752998/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2017-07-17","Electronic Tagging","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what programme management capabilities his Department has developed to oversee the future development of the new generation electronic monitoring programme.","false","Biography information for Richard Burgon","Leeds East","Richard Burgon","5595"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/752999","Ministry of Justice","false","2017-07-25","<p>We do not hold data on the number of staff who have left the National Probation Service due specifically to stress or ill health.</p><p> </p><p>Figures for the number of staff who left the National Probation Service through medical retirement or dismissal due to medical inefficiency are however available. Latest figures for these can be found in table 11a of the HMPPS annual workforce statistics bulletin 31 March 2017 at: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/614643/noms-workforce-tables-march-2017.xlsx" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/614643/noms-workforce-tables-march-2017.xlsx</a>.</p>","Aylesbury","Mr David Lidington",,"2017-07-25T13:58:27.407Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/752999/answer","Biography information for Sir David Lidington","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/752999/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/752999/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2017-07-17","National Probation Service for England and Wales: Resignations","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, how many staff have left the National Probation Service in the last 12 months due to (a) stress and (b) ill health.","false","Biography information for Richard Burgon","Leeds East","Richard Burgon","5586"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/753000","Ministry of Justice","false","2017-07-25","<p>Where an application for legal aid is made, this will be assessed against the existing means and merits tests, as appropriate. The Government has changed the law so that payments made to victims of the fire to support them, including from the Government’s discretionary fund, can be disregarded in assessments of financial eligibility for legal aid.</p><p> </p><p>The Government has worked collaboratively with the Law Society to design and issue guidance to legal aid providers so that they are best able to assist the residents.</p><p> </p><p>The Legal Aid Agency also continues to liaise directly with key partners on the ground at Grenfell, including the North Kensington Legal Centre who are offering advice through legal help.</p><p> </p>","Esher and Walton","Dominic Raab",,"2017-07-25T14:16:24.617Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/753000/answer","Biography information for Dominic Raab","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/753000/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/753000/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2017-07-17","Grenfell Tower: Fires","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what assistance the Government has provided to the residents of Grenfell Tower to enable them to access legal aid.","false","Biography information for Richard Burgon","Leeds East","Richard Burgon","5587"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/753001","Ministry of Justice","false","2017-07-25","<p>The illicit use of mobile phones undermines the safety and security of prisons. We are taking urgent and decisive action as the number of mobile phones and SIM cards seized continues to be too high.</p><p> </p><p>Between July 2016 and June 2017, the prison with the most mobile phones found was HMP Altcourse with 583.</p>","Aylesbury","Mr David Lidington",,"2017-07-25T13:54:15.22Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/753001/answer","Biography information for Sir David Lidington","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/753001/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/753001/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2017-07-17","Prisons: Mobile Phones","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, in which prison the largest number of phones was seized over the last 12 months.","false","Biography information for Richard Burgon","Leeds East","Richard Burgon","5596"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/753002","Ministry of Justice","false","2017-07-25","<p>We do not hold data on the number of prison officers who have left the prison service due specifically to stress or ill health.</p><p> </p><p>Figures for the number of prison officers who left the prison service through medical retirement or dismissal due to medical inefficiency are however available. Latest figures for these can be found in table 11b of the HMPPS annual workforce statistics bulletin 31 March 2017 at: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/614643/noms-workforce-tables-march-2017.xlsx" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/614643/noms-workforce-tables-march-2017.xlsx</a>.</p>","Aylesbury","Mr David Lidington",,"2017-07-25T13:57:20.823Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/753002/answer","Biography information for Sir David Lidington","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/753002/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/753002/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2017-07-17","Prison Officers: Resignations","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, how many prison officers have left the service due to (a) stress and (b) ill health in the last 12 months; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Richard Burgon","Leeds East","Richard Burgon","5588"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/753003","Ministry of Justice","false","2017-07-20","<p>The risks presented by the illicit use of drones in prisons are significant, as is the profound impact on prison safety and security. We rightly take a zero tolerance approach to smuggling of contraband into prisons and work closely with the police and Crown Prosecution Service (CPS) to ensure those caught are prosecuted. To date, there has been a total of 35 arrests and 11 convictions of criminals involved in drone activity – resulting in those convicted are sentenced to a total of more than 40 years in jail.</p><p> </p><p>I consider that there are risks presented by the publication of the data requested, which have the potential to cause further instability and increase violence and disorder in prisons, prejudicing the safe running of our institutions.</p><p> </p><p>The data requested would be likely to be used by some to subvert the effectiveness of our current counter measures. This is because the information is likely to prove invaluable to those engaged in criminality within prisons.</p><p> </p><p>Disclosure of this information could also prejudice any ongoing investigation of a drone incident and risk alerting possible suspects as well as weaken the possibilities of future arrests.</p>","East Surrey","Mr Sam Gyimah",,"2017-07-20T14:42:12.92Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/753003/answer","Biography information for Mr Sam Gyimah","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/753003/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/753003/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2017-07-17","Prisons: Unmanned Air Vehicles","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, with reference to the Answer of 16 November 2015 to Question 15648, and to the Answer of 17 July 2017 to Question 4436, for what reasons the policy on the disclosure of data on the seizures of drones in prisons has changed.","false","Biography information for Luciana Berger","Liverpool, Wavertree","Luciana Berger","5535"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/753004","Ministry of Justice","false","2017-07-25","<p>We are in the process of recruiting 2,500 new prison officers who receive substance misuse training as part of their overall training. This training includes identification of drugs and the impact they may have on health; signposting prisoners into relevant treatment/recovery services; and strategies to reduce supply and demand of drugs in prisons.</p><p> </p><p>Prisons have at their disposal a range of security measures to reduce the supply of drugs being smuggled into prisons including physical searching, the use of x-ray machines, CCTV surveillance cameras, intelligence-led searches and drug detection dogs. We have also introduced new national and regional intelligence units, and are investing over £3 million in creating counter-serious organised crime (SOC) units in HMPPS, which are working with establishments and law enforcement partners to develop intelligence on individuals and organised crime groups linked to the supply of drugs in prisons.</p><p> </p><p>To deter and disrupt the use of dangerous drugs, we are the first jurisdiction in the world to have developed and rolled out a new test for psychoactive substances (since September 2016) across the prison estate. We continue to work with our contracted laboratory to analyse data to ensure we are testing for the most commonly misused substances.</p><p>Governors are being empowered to deliver the changes that are most important for their prisons. From April 17, Governors have been given more freedom over how they organise their staff, including the ability to decide their staffing structure.</p><p> </p><p>In addition to this, since April 2017 governors have greater input into decision making about health provision in their prisons, enabling them to identify and work with NHS England commissioners to improve healthcare services in their prisons, including addiction services.</p>","Aylesbury","Mr David Lidington",,"2017-07-25T14:09:32.637Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/753004/answer","Biography information for Sir David Lidington","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/753004/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/753004/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2017-07-17","Prisons: Drugs","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what additional staffing resources the Government plans to allocate to prisons to enable officers and prison authorities to meet the objectives of the Government's new drugs strategy.","false","Biography information for Richard Burgon","Leeds East","Richard Burgon","5583"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/753005","Ministry of Justice","false","2017-07-20","<p>There is adequate car parking provision at Sunderland Magistrates’ Court for magistrates and court staff. There is no on-site parking provision for court users, however there is ample public car parking in the immediate vicinity of the court.</p>","Esher and Walton","Dominic Raab",,"2017-07-20T14:24:04.9Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/753005/answer","Biography information for Dominic Raab","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/753005/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/753005/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2017-07-17","Magistrates' Courts: Sunderland","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, whether Her Majesty's Courts and Tribunals Service has made an assessment of the adequacy of car parking provision at Sunderland Magistrates' Court.","false","Biography information for Bridget Phillipson","Houghton and Sunderland South","Bridget Phillipson","5569"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/753006","Northern Ireland Office","false","2017-07-21","<p>EU Exit affects a number of work areas across the Department and will therefore encompass a proportion of workload for many staff, the amount of which will vary over time. The Department has, however, set up a central EU Exit co-ordinating team, currently comprised of seven staff members.</p><p> </p>","Norwich North","Chloe Smith",,"2017-07-21T12:17:52.847Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/753006/answer","Biography information for Chloe Smith","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/753006/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/753006/answer",,,,,"21","Northern Ireland","Northern Ireland","2017-07-17","Northern Ireland Office: Brexit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Northern Ireland, how many staff in his Department have responsibilities relating to the UK leaving the EU.","false","Biography information for Hywel Williams","Arfon","Hywel Williams","5510"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/753007","Scotland Office","false","2017-07-20","<p>Staff in the Scotland Office cover a wide variety of issues important to Scotland, including work relating to exiting the EU.</p>","Dumfriesshire, Clydesdale and Tweeddale","David Mundell",,"2017-07-20T12:09:38.627Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/753007/answer","Biography information for David Mundell","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/753007/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/753007/answer",,,,,"2","Scotland","Scotland","2017-07-17","Scotland Office: Brexit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Scotland, how many staff in his Department have responsibilities relating to the UK leaving the EU.","false","Biography information for Hywel Williams","Arfon","Hywel Williams","5511"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/753008","Scotland Office","false","2017-07-21","<p>Copies of the digital adverts will not be added to the Library as they have already been published and are freely and easily accessible to the public online.</p>","Dumfriesshire, Clydesdale and Tweeddale","David Mundell",,"2017-07-21T12:11:45.987Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/753008/answer","Biography information for David Mundell","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/753008/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/753008/answer",,,,,"2","Scotland","Scotland","2017-07-17","Scotland Office: Social Media","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Scotland, pursuant to the Answer of 17 July 2017 to Question 3980, whether he will place in the Library copies of those advertisements.","false","Biography information for Deidre Brock","Edinburgh North and Leith","Deidre  Brock","5447"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/753009","Department for Transport","false","2017-07-21","<p>Specific information on the time taken to process an application where a licence has been suspended on medical grounds is not readily available.</p><p> </p><p>A dedicated team has been put in place which is responsible for continuous improvement of medical driver licensing services and communications. Letters to customers and medical professionals have been improved, helping to ensure that the Driver and Vehicle Licensing Agency receives the information it needs as quickly as possible.</p>","Hereford and South Herefordshire","Jesse Norman",,"2017-07-21T09:23:35.677Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/753009/answer","Biography information for Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/753009/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/753009/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-07-17","Driving: Licensing","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what the average time taken has been for the Driver and Vehicle Licensing Agency to process a re-application for a driving licence which has been suspended on medical grounds in each of the last seven years.","false","Biography information for Rachael Maskell","York Central","Rachael Maskell","5446"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/753010","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-07-31","<p>Through the Local Growth Fund, the Government is committing £12 billion to local areas in England between 2015 and 2021. £9.1 billion of this has been awarded through Growth Deals between Government and Local Enterprise Partnerships, of which the North West has been awarded £1.6 billion.</p>","Rossendale and Darwen","Jake Berry",,"2017-07-31T14:24:13.873Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/753010/answer","Biography information for Jake Berry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/753010/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/753010/answer","Rossendale and Darwen","Jake Berry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/753010/answer/previousversion/6576","Biography information for Jake Berry","7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-07-17","Local Growth Deals","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, pursuant to the Answer of 1 July 2017 to Question 3183, how much funding has been allocated to (a) the UK, (b) England and (c) North West England; and how much each of those constituent parts has been allocated through the Local Growth Fund.","false","Biography information for Bill Esterson","Sefton Central","Bill Esterson","5458"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/753011","Department for Transport","false","2017-07-24","<p>The Department for Transport set up a new Directorate last year to co-ordinate its EU Exit work alongside its existing EU and International work. Staff within the Directorate lead on providing advice to Ministers on EU Exit and exit-related issues. Members of staff across the Department also provide advice and analysis on EU Exit issues as required. Given the interactions between EU exit work and the Department’s other priorities, it is not possible to give an accurate figure.</p>","Hereford and South Herefordshire","Jesse Norman",,"2017-07-24T13:54:25.153Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/753011/answer","Biography information for Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/753011/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/753011/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-07-17","Department for Transport: Brexit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, how many staff in his Department have responsibilities relating to the UK leaving the EU.","false","Biography information for Hywel Williams","Arfon","Hywel Williams","5513"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/753012","Department for Transport","false","2017-07-20","<p>The government has made no estimate of the number of UK seafarers able to call or have Skype conversations with friends and family in the UK when they are in foreign ports.</p><p> </p><p>Similar to foreign seafarers in UK ports, UK seafarers are able to use the services of seafarer welfare providers in foreign ports, such as free wi-fi, to call or have Skype conversations with people in the UK. In addition, some major foreign ports and shipowners allow UK seafarers to use their wi-fi for free</p>","South Holland and The Deepings","Mr John Hayes",,"2017-07-20T09:48:03.787Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/753012/answer","Biography information for Sir John Hayes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/753012/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/753012/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-07-17","Shipping: Telecommunications","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, pursuant to the Answer of 17 July 2017 to Question 4563, what estimate he has made of the number of UK seafarers able to call or have Skype conversations with friends and family in the UK when they are in foreign ports.","false","Biography information for Bill Esterson","Sefton Central","Bill Esterson","5459"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/753013","Department for Transport","false","2017-07-20","<p>There are no plans to consult on options to link HS2 to the Port of Liverpool. The government and Transport for the North continue to develop a single integrated strategy for Northern Powerhouse Rail, including a range of options for Manchester to Liverpool, and the wider NPR network. Options outlined in the Crewe Hub consultation could also result in faster journey times for some Liverpool services.</p>","Blackpool North and Cleveleys","Paul Maynard",,"2017-07-20T09:44:43.163Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/753013/answer","Biography information for Paul Maynard","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/753013/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/753013/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-07-17","High Speed 2 Railway Line: Liverpool Port","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, whether he plans to include options to link HS2 to the Port of Liverpool in the consultation announced on 17 July 2017.","false","Biography information for Bill Esterson","Sefton Central","Bill Esterson","5460"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/753014","Department for Transport","false","2017-07-21","<p>Highways England continue to carry out all routine maintenance duties on the A14 through their service provider to ensure that this strategically important route remains in a safe and serviceable condition. This includes undertaking routine weekly safety inspections to identify, prioritise and address any defects found.</p><p><br>Where work on the A14 Cambridge to Huntingdon Improvement scheme is being carried out close to the existing carriageway, Highways England has implemented narrow lanes and speed restrictions to protect drivers as works progress. Along this section of the route CCTV continuously monitors traffic and a free recovery service is provided to road users who need assistance.</p><p> </p>","Hereford and South Herefordshire","Jesse Norman",,"2017-07-21T10:10:33.663Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/753014/answer","Biography information for Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/753014/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/753014/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-07-17","A14: Safety","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what steps his Department is taking to ensure that the A14 will remain safe for driving until its rebuild in 2020.","false","Biography information for Daniel Zeichner","Cambridge","Daniel Zeichner","5564"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/753015","Department for Transport","false","2017-07-21","<p>The new Euston station will be an interchange fit for the 21<sup>st</sup> century and designed to handle the ever increasing demands on our rail network.</p><p> </p><p>To ensure the expanded Euston station is able to manage the additional passengers, we will be upgrading the existing underground interchange. There will be new direct access between high speed rail platforms and the Underground, new circulation areas to relieve overcrowding, new routes down to the Victoria and Northern Lines, new underground access to Euston Square Station (Circle, Metropolitan and Hammersmith &amp; City Lines) and new access to the Northern line Charing Cross branch.</p><p> </p><p>In addition, we estimate that one third of HS2 passengers will use Old Oak Common as their connection hub rather than Euston, accessing Crossrail and Great Western Mainline services to get to central London, Heathrow and the South West.</p>","Blackpool North and Cleveleys","Paul Maynard",,"2017-07-21T11:27:57.267Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/753015/answer","Biography information for Paul Maynard","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/753015/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/753015/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-07-17","Euston Station: Passengers","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what plans he has to ensure that Euston Station can cope with the additional volume of passengers expected as a result of High Speed 2.","false","Biography information for Mr David Lammy","Tottenham","Mr David Lammy","5558"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/753016","Wales Office","false","2017-07-20","<p>The Department for Exiting the European Union has responsibility for overseeing preparations for the withdrawal of the UK from the EU and conducting these withdrawal negotiations in support of the Prime Minister. In doing this it is working very closely with other Government departments, including the Wales Office.</p><p>The Wales Office has refocused its priorities following the United Kingdom’s vote to leave the European Union and work relating to exiting the EU now forms part of the policy portfolio of most staff.</p>","Vale of Glamorgan","Alun Cairns",,"2017-07-20T11:10:16.583Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/753016/answer","Biography information for Alun Cairns","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/753016/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/753016/answer",,,,,"28","Wales","Wales","2017-07-17","Wales Office: Brexit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Wales, how many staff in his Department have responsibilities relating to the UK leaving the EU.","false","Biography information for Hywel Williams","Arfon","Hywel Williams","5514"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/753017","Wales Office","false","2017-07-20","<p>The European Union (Withdrawal) Bill establishes a transitional arrangement that replicates current EU frameworks in UK law, referred to as retained EU law. The Government is now beginning intensive discussions with the devolved administrations about where common frameworks are needed in the areas covered by the transitional arrangement. Where frameworks are not needed, the Bill provides a mechanism for passing powers to the devolved nations.</p><p> </p>","Vale of Glamorgan","Alun Cairns",,"2017-07-20T11:03:06.8Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/753017/answer","Biography information for Alun Cairns","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/753017/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/753017/answer",,,,,"28","Wales","Wales","2017-07-17","European Union (Withdrawal) Bill: Wales","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Wales, pursuant to the Answer of 3 July 2017 to Question 982, for what reason the European Union (Withdrawal) Bill makes no reference to powers set to be devolved to the National Assembly for Wales.","false","Biography information for Paul Flynn","Newport West","Paul Flynn","5541"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/753018","Women and Equalities","false","2017-07-25","<p>I will be placing in the library of both Houses the letter of appointment that was sent to Lord Shinkwin on 21 April 2017 appointing him to the Equality and Human Rights Commission Board.</p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb",,"2017-07-25T16:37:31.077Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/753018/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/753018/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/753018/answer",,,,,"31","Women and Equalities","Women and Equalities","2017-07-17","Equality and Human Rights Commission","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for Women and Equalities, if she will place in the Library of both Houses records of communications that exist on the appointment of Lord Shinkwin to the Equality and Human Rights Commission from or to any (a) member Board of the Equality and Human Rights Commission, (b) employee of the Human Rights Commission and (c) member of the Disability Advisory Committee of the Equality and Human Rights Commission.","false","Biography information for Heidi Allen","South Cambridgeshire","Heidi Allen","5603"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/753019","Women and Equalities","false","2017-07-25","<p>About ten staff in the Government Equalities Office (GEO) and its legal advisers, particularly those dealing with equalities legislation and international matters, work as necessary on the UK leaving the EU, though none are employed full-time on this issue.</p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2017-07-25T16:31:42.883Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/753019/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/753019/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/753019/answer",,,,,"31","Women and Equalities","Women and Equalities","2017-07-17","Government Equalities Office: Brexit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for Women and Equalities, how many staff in the Government Equalities Office have responsibilities relating to the UK leaving the EU.","false","Biography information for Hywel Williams","Arfon","Hywel Williams","5512"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/753020","Women and Equalities","false","2017-07-24","<p>The Equality and Human Rights Commission is an independent public body and decisions about the roles and responsibilities of its Board members, and how these are communicated within the organisation, are matters for the Commission itself. I have therefore asked the Commission’s Chief Executive Officer to write to the my hon. Friend with the information requested. I will place a copy of the letter in the libraries of both Houses.</p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb","5381 ; 5382 ; 5435 ; 5576","2017-07-24T16:29:02.66Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/753020/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/753020/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/753020/answer",,,,,"31","Women and Equalities","Women and Equalities","2017-07-17","Equality and Human Rights Commission","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for Women and Equalities, whether the decision to abolish the post of Disability Commissioner in 2017 was taken outside of an Equality and Human Rights Commission board meeting; whether the standard procedure for the board to make decisions outside of board meetings was followed; what electronic or hard copy records exist of communications relating to (a) the possibility of abolishing and (b) the decision to abolish the post of Disability Commissioner in 2017 (i) from or to individual board members and (ii) by any employees of the Equality and Human Rights Commission; and if she will place a copy of those records in the Library.","false","Biography information for Heidi Allen","South Cambridgeshire","Heidi Allen","5436"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/753021","Women and Equalities","false","2017-07-24","<p>The Equality and Human Rights Commission is an independent public body and decisions about the roles and responsibilities of its Board members, and how these are communicated within the organisation, are matters for the Commission itself. I have therefore asked the Commission’s Chief Executive Officer to write to the my hon. Friend with the information requested. I will place a copy of the letter in the libraries of both Houses.</p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb","5381 ; 5382 ; 5436 ; 5576","2017-07-24T16:29:02.54Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/753021/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/753021/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/753021/answer",,,,,"31","Women and Equalities","Women and Equalities","2017-07-17","Equality and Human Rights Commission","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for Women and Equalities, what process the board of the Equality and Human Rights Commission uses to take decisions outside of formal board meetings.","false","Biography information for Heidi Allen","South Cambridgeshire","Heidi Allen","5435"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/753022","Women and Equalities","false","2017-07-24","<p>The Equality and Human Rights Commission is an independent public body and decisions about the roles and responsibilities of its Board members, and how these are communicated within the organisation, are matters for the Commission itself. I have therefore asked the Commission’s Chief Executive Officer to write to the my hon. Friend with the information requested. I will place a copy of the letter in the libraries of both Houses.</p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb","5381 ; 5382 ; 5435 ; 5436","2017-07-24T16:29:02.77Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/753022/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/753022/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/753022/answer",,,,,"31","Women and Equalities","Women and Equalities","2017-07-17","Equality and Human Rights Commission","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for Women and Equalities, on which dates the Board of the Equality and Human Rights Commission (a) discussed and (b) approved the abolition of the post of Disability Commissioner; and whether the decision was (i) voted on, (ii) approved unanimously or (iii) subject to a majority vote.","false","Biography information for Heidi Allen","South Cambridgeshire","Heidi Allen","5576"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/753023","Women and Equalities","false","2017-07-27","<p>Healthcare is devolved to Northern Ireland so this is a matter for the Northern Ireland (NI) Government. The recent decision to fund abortions in England for women usually resident in NI does not affect this position.</p>","Guildford","Anne Milton",,"2017-07-27T17:54:59.4Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/753023/answer","Biography information for Anne Milton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/753023/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/753023/answer",,,,,"31","Women and Equalities","Women and Equalities","2017-07-17","Maternity Services: Northern Ireland","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for Women and Equalities, whether the Government plans to offer support to Northern Irish women to carry their children through to term in the light of the support it is extending to women in Northern Ireland seeking support to have an abortion on the NHS in England.","false","Biography information for Paul Girvan","South Antrim","Paul Girvan","5601"
